    "summarizer": {
      "general_reader_takeaway": "This paper presents new, highly precise measurements of the cosmic microwave background (CMB) \u2014 the faint afterglow of the Big Bang \u2014 using the South Pole Telescope. For the first time, a combination of two ground-based telescopes (SPT and ACT) matches the precision of the space-based Planck satellite on key cosmological parameters, which the review board found to be a genuine milestone. The analysis is technically serious and extensively validated, though several systematic corrections were added after the main pipeline was locked, and some internal consistency checks required manual workarounds. The most consequential open question is whether a roughly 2.8\u03c3 discrepancy found between the CMB results and galaxy-survey (DESI) measurements signals new physics beyond the standard cosmological model.",
      "reviewer": "claude",
      "technical_takeaway": "The paper presents SPT-3G D1 TT/TE/EE band powers from 2019\u20132020 Main-field observations (~4% sky, coadded noise ~2.4 \u03bcK-arcmin in temperature and ~3.4 \u03bcK-arcmin in polarization), claiming the most precise lensed EE measurements at \u2113~1000\u20134000 and TE at \u2113~1000\u20133000, and the first ground-based CMB combination (SPT+ACT) reaching Planck constraining power on some parameters. Methodological advances include a curved-sky HEALPix pipeline, first-use Gaussian-constrained inpainting for primary CMB T&E analysis, a JAX-based differentiable likelihood (candl), and a semi-analytic covariance framework. Cosmological constraints are reported as consistent with \u039bCDM and with Planck/ACT DR6; a ~2.8\u03c3 CMB\u2013DESI DR2 BAO tension is reported in \u039bCDM, relaxed in extended models. Key technical caveats surviving cross-review are: non-trivial post-unblinding systematic corrections (quadrupolar beam leakage detected at 3.5\u20136\u03c3, polarized beam sidelobe model), covariance matrix regularization required to pass conditional consistency tests, and formal TT null-test failures accepted with a post-hoc justification not pre-registered in the blinding protocol. None of these were assessed as fatal; all three reviewers recommended selection."
